<font color="#FF0000">EX-DRUG CRAZED VIETNAM VET?</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jul 26  3:14:03 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Gosh, Darn doc, you peed  all over yourself and I can see you did it twice.<br><br>
Here I was bringing my own heat tab and the last can of  C-rations (Lima Beans) just to show you what a real meal looks like. <br><br>
Spatz, you would be surprise at what I do for a living and yes, I have spent hundreds and hundreds of hours listening and counseling with many, many Vietnam veterans and helping them get their lives together. Especially those that have suffered under the ill advise of shrinks like you that have turned their badge of honor into pains of guilt and sorrow. <br><br>
As for Chet &quot;Ex-drug crazed Vietnam Vet&quot;?  I did not do drugs, I can count in one hand the Marines that at one time or another experimented with pot during the whole 13 months I served in Vietnam. There were over 300 Marines in my company alone and to this day, I do not know of any one of them being a drug crazed Vietnam Vet. Its insinuations like that Doc and others jump on to come to their conclusions about Vietnam Veterans.<br><br>
I don't expect Spatz to change his stripes, and unlike you, I do not respect his views. They are wrong and while everyone here seems to take a, well lets talk about and consider other point of view the truth of the matter is doc has been stringing everyone all along.  The silence has prevailed for far too long and the American people are finally beginning to understand that the War in Nam was a just war. Now is not the time to cease firing. To hold back and go to the conference table. Johnson did that, and look where it got us. <br>
It is a black and white world. It is the forces of darkness against the forces of light. Compromise is what Johnson was all about.<br>
Doc prides himself as a Conscientious Objector and I can respect a guy that just outright says he's a coward or does not believe in war. Those type of people can fill sandbags or burn shitters if they want to, but don't get in the way of those answering their country's call. I would not want a CO at my side or anywhere near me in a battle zone. Those types of people WERE THE BABY KILLERS who did so to get out of fighting a worthy foe, because they were scared and afraid to die. <br>
What's wrong with doc's point of view is that he decided to play God. He figured out what was right for the country and what was right for all of us. But, it is because of gutless wimps like him that this country suffered its darkest hour. <br><br>
On May 31, 1968 following one of the fiercest firefight, I had ever been engaged in, we swept through the area looking for survivors of the battle. That morning fifteen feet from the edge of the road in a cluster of tall broad leaf trees that were splattered with the blood of the enemy, I found a large NVA soldier. <br>
He had been only slightly wounded but was wide eyed, alive, and sitting upright. I walked up to him and removed the AK-47 that was laid across his lap. The rifle was brand new; IT HAD NEVER BEEN FIRED. <br>
The soldiers uniform was clean and freshly laundered there was a visible crease line along the front of his uniform as if he had just picked it up at the local Laundromat. He was a Chinese Communist military advisor, fully clothed in his brand new Chinese made military uniform. He possessed Chinese identification and was fully armed with the latest weapon his country could produce.  As I approached him, I could see that he was in a state of shock and scared. I motioned him to stand up and he quickly obeyed. <br>
In light of the firefight, we had just experienced the day before I envied his cowardliness.  I found myself almost praising his steadfastness amidst the fierce fighting that he must have witnessed.  I knew I had melted a machine guns barrel fighting against his compatriots the day before. Many Marines had been killed or wounded on both sides of my machine gun. Somehow during the battle I had been separated from my unit and found myself fighting along side of the Marines from Charlie Company 1/7, where the battle was the thickest. History shows that it was one of that unit's darkest days in their history of the Vietnam War. We were fighting a well-entrenched, well-disciplined communist force and they had sprung a successful ambush. Truly from the beginning, they had the upper hand.<br>
The brand new AK-47 I recovered was mine to keep if I wanted it. The spoils of war, doc, but you wouldn't understand that. But, perhaps you will understand this. <br>
A month later when I went to board the plane going home I was told that I would have to stay an extra day to have the rifles bore lead filled as it was an automatic weapon. As much as I would have liked to have kept that brand new weapon, I realized that the weapon had belonged to a coward and not real fighting man and so without hesitation, I left it behind. <br>
Yet, I still respect that Commie more then a conscientious objector that would dare to call himself an American patriot. WHAT DID YOU DO DURING THE WAR, DADDY? That's what really bugs you Spatz, your heart can no longer justify what your mind has told it all these years. <br><br>

